bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: The George Washington University Medical Center is comprised of School of Medicine and Health Sciences, the University Hospital (including the Women's Board, which was formed in 1898), and the University Clinic (Ambulatory Care Center).

The medical school was opened in 1825 and is the eleventh oldest in the nation. From 1868-1973 it was located at 1335 H Street, NW. In 1973 it moved to Walter G. Ross Hall and the Himmelfarb Medical Library. All aspects of the Medical Center -hospital, medical school, and research facilities - were centralized at last. The hospital had been located at 1335 H Street until 1948, when a new hospital was built on Washington Circle.
A new hospital was constructed in 2002 across the street from the old one. The University Clinic opened in 1969 on Pennsylvania Avenue and was expanded to house the Ambulatory Care Center in 1988.

In 1981 the Medical Center's staff made front-page news when President Reagan, shot at close range, was rushed to the GW emergency room. The fine service that saved the president's life was commemorated 10 years later by the establishment of the Ronald Reagan Institute of Emergency Medicine to train emergency system coordinators and pursue basic and clinical research in emergency medicine.

The Medical Center publishes Progress (1989-Present), which evolved from the Friday Report (1970-89), and GW Health and Medicine magazine (1965-Present). The Vice President for Health Affairs (which oversees the Medical Center) reports to the President.
N.B. This history note was written in 2005

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include personnel files, minutes, correspondence, yearbooks, newsletters, publications, photographs, negatives, by-laws, scrapbooks, telephone directories, films, and videotapes. They range in date from dates from 1825-2011, and were transferred to the University Archives by the Director of the Medical Center. Note that not all series have been processed. Please see staff for assistance.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into thirty-one series: Personnel files; Medical staff office files; Personnel files; Articles and studies; Reprints; Chartering ceremony (currently missing); Photographs and negatives; Reports; Statistics of medical school; Women's board; Committee files; Inactive physicians files; Inactive physicians files; Women's board; Alumni Association for Health Services Management; Health Services Management and Policy Alumni Association; Women's board; Telephone directories; Publication; Department of Pharmacology reprints; Films; School of Public Health and Health Services; Women's Board; Photographs, papers, and videotapes; Yearbooks; Friday Report; GW Medicine/Health magazine; Photographs; State Health Notes newsletter; Progress newsletter; Records.

scopecontent.p: This series includes correspondence, brochures, floor plans, memorandums, executive summaries, reports, publications, programs, articles, press releases, calendar of events, schedules, reports, vitas, applications, agendas, meeting minutes, speeches, course catalogues, window stickers, forms, posters, and applications. They range in date from 1825 to 2004. The materials concern the Medical Center, lectures, services, patient education, the Allergy Clinic, audiovisual services, diets, budgets, the Center for Health Policy Research, the Center to Improve Care of the Dying, the Health Policy committee, conferences, computer applications, dedication of Ross Hall, symposiums, several departmental publications, films, various public health information brochures, medical research, residency programs, financial planning, University Hospital, internships, fellowships, research, committees, ethics, the Medical Association of the District of Columbia, history of the School of Medicine, planning, opening assemblies, closing assemblies, seminars, the School of Medicine and Health Sciences, "GWU Prognosis", admissions, financial assistance, the School of Public Health and Health Services, the National Health Policy Forum, seminars, and the Department of Public Health program. Some people mentioned include Dr. Frank Nelson Miller, Jr., Dr. Seymour Alpert, John Parks, and Angus M. Griffin. Some brochures are in Spanish.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The George Washington University Health Plan was proposed by the Division of General Medicine in the Department of Medicine in 1971. Dr. Thomas Piemme was the Director of the Division. Piemme had made his intentions known to the Chair of Medicine, Wallace Jensen, to the Dean, John Parks, and to the Associate Dean for Clinical Affairs, James Feffer before he arrived at the University on January 1, 1970 – and had their approval. Moreover, he had a "Special Project Grant" from the Bureau of Health Manpower in which development of an HMO was a part.

During the summer of 1971. Jim Feffer and Dr. Piemme attended a conference in Los Angeles, conducted by the Kaiser Health Plan, to learn the fundamentals of organizing pre-paid health plans. Piemme was joined in the Division in early 1971 by Steven A. Schroeder, whom he had recruited from Harvard.

Together, Steve and Dr. Piemme then visited Harvard, Yale, and Johns Hopkins – the three medical schools that, at the time, had developed university-based HMOs. During the course of their travels and other research, they accumulated the documents necessary to an understanding of what they were about to recommend. The men then wrote a proposal that was submitted to Lloyd Elliott, President of the University.
In early 1972 Dr. Elliott wrote to Dr. Piemme approving the plan to proceed.
